cabulary words have. It's only been written as\nmoreover as one word like this for about 600-ish years. Finally, for conversely, we've got con, which means with or together,\nverse meaning to turn, so the converse of something\nis all turned around, the opposite, and then\nthere's our old friend -ly, the adverb forming suffix. So to do something conversely\nis to do it in a way that is all turned around or opposite. Time for using these\nwords in some sentences. \"It's critical to remember that you can have too\nmuch of a good thing. A little bit of banana and\npickle frosting is delicious, but too much can make you very sick.\" - [Gingabeeb] Banana and\npickle frosting sounds gross. - [David] Oh, ye of\nlittle faith. Next one. \"Colorblindness is a\nrelatively rare condition. Approximately one in every 12 men and one in every 200 women\nstruggle to tell the difference between certain colors,\nlike red and green.\" It's not exactly one in 12\nmen and one in 200 women, it's around that number. \"Moreover, it has made my job\nat the traffic light factory a living nightmare.\" Last one, \"On the one hand, it\nwould be cool to time travel to the age of the dinosaurs. Conversely, on the other\nhand,\" in an opposite way, \"I would rather not be\neaten by velociraptors.\" No snappy retort, Gingabeeb? - [Gingabeeb] No, those were\npretty good sentences actually. I learned a lot. - [David] Thank goodness. All right, I'll see you in\nthe next one, wordsmiths. Until then, you can learn\nanything. David out. - [Gingabeeb] And I'll see\nyou in the next one, David. - [David] Gingabeeb, is that a threat? - [Gingabeeb] It's a promise."
